1.2 — System Doctrine (Unchanged — Re-stated for Context Anchoring)
All 10 doctrines from Part #1 remain in full force. For quick reference:
DOCTRINE-001: Event tables are STRICTLY append-only. No UPDATE, no DELETE for app roles.
DOCTRINE-002: All authoritative timestamps via database NOW() synchronized to NTP. Client timestamps NEVER authoritative.
DOCTRINE-003: Drivers are unauthenticated. Short-lived server-issued tokens only.
DOCTRINE-004: No ‘super admin’ mutation paths. No human can UPDATE/DELETE event records.
DOCTRINE-005: system_lifecycle_worker role for automated retention expiry only.
DOCTRINE-006: Session IDs are atomic, unique, non-mergeable. No overlapping sessions.
DOCTRINE-007: Every event is SHA-256 hashed and chain-linked.
DOCTRINE-008: QR codes identify location only. Authority enforced server-side.
DOCTRINE-009: Driver annotations NEVER change session state, timestamps, or prior events.
DOCTRINE-010: System-authority events bypass human roles entirely.
1.3 — New Doctrines Introduced in Part #2
DOCTRINE-011: Facility claims (PAPERWORK_READY, etc.) are DECLARATIONS, not PROOFS.
  - They record what the facility ASSERTS, not what objectively occurred.
  - The system labels them as facility-declared and makes NO inference about
    detention, liability, fault, or whether the driver was actually served.

DOCTRINE-012: Conflicts are PRESERVED, never RESOLVED by the system.
  - When a driver disagrees with a facility claim, BOTH records coexist permanently.
  - The system does not decide who is correct. It does not adjudicate.
  - Both the facility claim and the driver disagreement remain visible in the
    evidence packet, side by side, for external parties to evaluate.

DOCTRINE-013: Facility events do NOT change session status.
  - PAPERWORK_READY does not close the session.
  - PAPERWORK_READY does not imply CHECK_OUT.
  - Session closure requires: explicit CHECK_OUT scan, manual facility close,
    or system timeout. NOTHING else.
