SECTION 4 — DRIVER DISAGREEMENT & CONFLICT PRESERVATION
This section implements the most legally significant pattern in EvidenceLedger: when a driver disagrees with a facility claim, the system preserves BOTH statements without resolving the conflict.
4.1 — The Disagreement Scenario (Exact Specification)
This is the complete, step-by-step reality of what happens:
Step A: A warehouse staff member presses the ‘Paperwork Ready’ button. The system creates a permanent PAPERWORK_READY event with the NTP-verified timestamp (e.g., 14:30:23 UTC). This record cannot be changed or deleted. It shows only what the facility says, not what is proven to be true.
Step B: The driver disagrees. The driver is still waiting and believes the paperwork was NOT ready at that time. The driver adds an annotation via the annotation page (built in Part #1). A typical annotation: ‘Paperwork was not handed to me yet. Still waiting at the dock.’
Step C: The driver’s DRIVER_NOTE event is recorded with referenced_event_id pointing to the PAPERWORK_READY event. This creates an explicit, auditable link between the claim and the disagreement.
Step D: The facility does nothing else. It does not correct itself. It does not acknowledge the disagreement.
Step E: The system keeps BOTH statements. The system does NOT decide who is right. The system does NOT fix the conflict. The system does NOT take sides. Both records remain visible forever, side by side.

4.2 — Technical Implementation of Disagreement Linking
The Part #1 annotation system already supports referenced_event_id. For Part #2, extend the annotation UI to enable explicit disagreement linking:
•	When the driver views their annotation page and a PAPERWORK_READY event exists in the session, display a prominent banner: ‘The facility has declared paperwork ready at [timestamp]. Do you agree?’
•	Provide two paths: (A) ‘I agree’ — no annotation needed, driver acknowledges silently. (B) ‘I disagree — add my note’ — opens the annotation form with referenced_event_id pre-filled to the PAPERWORK_READY event’s ID.
•	The ‘I agree’ button does NOT create any event. Agreement is absence of disagreement. This prevents gaming where a facility pressures drivers to ‘confirm.’
•	The annotation form must show the facility claim’s timestamp alongside the driver’s note for context.
4.3 — System Trigger: Flag Disagreement
-- When a DRIVER_NOTE is inserted that references a PAPERWORK_READY event,
-- update the facility_claims projection table:

CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION flag_driver_disagreement()
  RETURNS TRIGGER AS $$
BEGIN
  IF NEW.event_type = 'DRIVER_NOTE' AND NEW.referenced_event_id IS NOT NULL THEN
    UPDATE facility_claims
      SET has_driver_disagreement = true
      WHERE event_id = NEW.referenced_event_id;
  END IF;
  RETURN NEW;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql SECURITY DEFINER;

CREATE TRIGGER trg_flag_disagreement
  AFTER INSERT ON session_events
  FOR EACH ROW
  EXECUTE FUNCTION flag_driver_disagreement();

-- NOTE: This is the ONLY mutation of facility_claims.has_driver_disagreement.
-- It is a system trigger, not a human-accessible path.
-- DOCTRINE-012 is preserved: the system flags the conflict but does not resolve it.
⚠ CONFLICT PRESERVATION INVARIANT
Verify: (1) The system NEVER deletes the facility claim when a driver disagrees. (2) The system NEVER deletes the driver note. (3) The system NEVER modifies either record's content or timestamp. (4) The flag_driver_disagreement trigger ONLY sets has_driver_disagreement = true, never false. (5) There is NO ‘resolve conflict’ API endpoint, button, or mechanism anywhere in the system.


